Drop-in replacement for the short belts. This design is somewhat incomplete. I did not finalize the design because my alternative approach (Floating short belt tensioner http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:179286) was successfull while being significantly less complex. This proof of concept works surprisingly well if printed at sufficient quality to meet the strict tolerances of the gear pairings. Finalizing the design essentially would require some fine adjustments to the clearances of the screw heads, reinforcing the mounts and other minor cleanup. Maybe I will get back to this later. I put the design here because I think it is still an interesting implementation of the direct drive concept. Other concepts around include bulky external assemblies. I didn't want to mess up my UM's great aesthetic value and create a virtually invisible direct drive that does not require too much tinkering.

Print at highest quality possible. The gear pairings will only work without jamming or play if printed perfectly round and smooth. Break in the gears carefully to remove edges and bumps. Gear wheel print quality is essential. The slightest imperfection will introduce jamming or backlash. Try to interchange the gears to find perfectly matching pairs. Reprint and try again before installing the device! You will not be able to print improved wheels with an imprfect assembly in place. Think before you spend hours for installing and rolling back your UM to the belts. Like I did... ;-) Bill of materials:
  • 6 ball bearings 10x3x3
  • Machine screws of different length (you will have to cut them to the right length anyway)
  • 4 headless screws M3
  • 6 washers M3
  • 6 nuts M3 (self locking or Loctite)

title: Geeetech i3 Pro C Dual Extruder X-axis width fix

description.text:
Geeetech's own dual extruder upgrade for their i3 prusa printer keeps the standard single extruder printer dimensions. Each of the extruders is offset by 16mm from center. This limits the build volume to about 184mm wide when using a single extruder, and only 168mm wide using both extruders.

My upgrade offsets the bottom and top Z-axis mounts out by 16mm in either direction. This restores the full 200mm wide build volume while using both extruders. The upper mounts have a larger hole for the threaded rod to reduce Z-axis wobble.

I also had a problem with the X-axis travel being limited by the X-axis tensioner bolt. I designed a new tensioner mount outside of the Z-axis mount. This modification requires cutting a larger opening from the Z-axis mount for the belt. Taking Chris_Vanclercq's idea, I have also posted designs where the right-side Z-axis is offset by 26mm so that you can use the original X-axis tensioner. The 26mm mod has not been tested on my printer.

In addition to these 3D printed parts, longer 8mm rods are needed for the X-axis (minimum 205mm length or 215mm length for the 26mm offset parts), as well as a 1m long GT2 belt.

description.text:
December 11th, 2017 - uploaded "Nacelle_Inner_Left_0manifolds.stl" and "Nacelle_Outer_Left_0_Manifolds.stl" these should have zero non-manifolds in them and they show good in both Cura and Slic3r Prusa Edition; to print the Right nacelle just mirror these two models.

September 23rd 2017 - Uploaded Roll_Bar_Back.stl; zero non-manifolds in Blender

September 22nd 2017 - Uploaded Roll_Bar_Front.stl, zero Non-Manifolds in Blender

September 21st 2017 - Uploaded (Saucer_Top_1 and Saucer_Top_2) re-meshed in blender. in both models there is one non-manifold that I cannot get rid of. in Blender it states it is a duplicate vertices but it isn't. Version 1 is the one with the roll bar supports, version 2 is without.

September 5th 2017 - Uploaded the bottom saucer re-mixed again in blender. There are two non-manifolds in the model but they do not appear to mess with anything in the model when slicing, currently working on the top saucer.

August 29th, 2017 - Currently re-working this model using what I learned when cutting the Intrepid Class so moving this model back into the Work-in-Progress classification until I have re-worked the model. Found a lot of Non-Manifolds and currently working on the Bottom_Saucer piece as it was the one with the most.

July 26th, 2017 - uploaded an alternate version of the top saucer, this one is for ships like the "Lantree" that did not have the roll-bar so now that variant can be printed if desired

Okay just found and fixed an issue with this model, apparently i used the wrong source for the size of the ship, the measurement I was basing on was 277 meters for the length and I found another source stating that 237 is the length. The 237 length fits in well with the Constitution class and the Constellation Class (the saucers for these are basically the same model with a few additions and modifications) The correct Scale model has been uploaded

This is a remix of the Miranda Class starship uploaded by nd4spd1919
Basically I have cut it up into 8 pieces for printing

i have already successfully printed out the rollbar and the engine nacelles and am currently printing the top half of the saucer, however I do not think I have enough filament left over to complete that print. So I am going to be loading this up as a Work in Progress until a shipment of Filament arrives (hopefully around Oct.19)

Cura's Estimation of Print time and Print time so far:

Saucer Top 5Hr 3min
Saucer Bottom 5Hr
Rollbar 1Hr
Engines 2Hr 24Min

Printer:

Anet A8

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

5%

Notes:

I did something a little bit different with this remix.
The top and bottom saucer sections include the supports for the roll bar and the nacelles
The nacelles have a small groove in them so that they can be connected to the supports more easily
the roll bar is in two pieces, when glued together where the phaser emitters and the supports meet are there is a small groove to connect to the pieces together.

title: Modifications for The Great Fredini's Scan o Tron 3000

description.text:
We modified a few parts of Fredini's Scan o Tron 3000 for easier assembly.  
We added holes for the bolts in the carriage hinge so no drilling is necessary.

the space between the case and head is called a heat break this allows the tube to maintain a cooler temp than the hot-end

m3x10 long set screw for auto calibration cut at the same height as the tip of the hot end

description.text:
As a FYI There is a License agreement with this Download and If you do download these STL file you are agreeing to the license.

Just a word of caution. There are electronics and battery being used and this project so adult supervision for children is advised.

Created in Lightwave.

I want to expand on the UFO that a made earlier this year and came up with this design.

Also I want to point out that my knowledge of electronics is armature at best. So please do your research if you don't know what your doing.

For the Glass file I printed it then, made a mold of it, then poured clear resin to get the final look but not as clear as I wanted.

Tools that used :

  1. Files of various shapes.
  2. Super Glue.
  3. hand held drill with small drill bits.
  4. Soldering iron with solder.
  5. pliers for cutting and striping wires.

3D Printed Parts:

  1. Handle Grip A (X1)
  2. Handle Grip B (X1)
  3. Handle (X1)
  4. Handle Peg (X2)
  5. Spaceship Top (X1)
  6. Spaceship Bottom (X1)
  7. Spaceship Window (X1)
  8. Spaceship Tracker beam (X1)
  9. Glass (X1)
    10.Moon (X1)
  10. Moon Cover (X1)
  11. Battery Clip (x1) If used

Electronic used: Adafruit

  1. NeoPixel Ring - https://www.adafruit.com/products/1463
  2. Adafruit Pro Trinket - https://www.adafruit.com/products/2000
  3. Arduino Uno R3 (Atmega328 - https://www.adafruit.com/products/50
  4. 16mm Illuminated Pushbutton - https://www.adafruit.com/products/1440
  5. Cable - https://www.adafruit.com/products/592
  6. resistor (X2) (I used 470 and it thick it was either 1/4 amp or 1/2 amp)
  7. AA Cylindrical Battery Contacts, Clips, Holders & Springs.( I used 4)
  8. Hook-up wires (https://www.sparkfun.com/products/11375)
  9. 9v connector

Software:
Arduino IDE

The only thing that's not mine is the code for the light effect that belongs to Pat. Once I get Pat's permission to distribute his code to others I will update but, until then you can use the one that comes with the Adruino IDE from the library Adafruit Neo Pixel (you will need to install it), Example Buttoncycler.

Just a quick explanation to help assemble the pieces together.

  1. Put together the top and bottom UFO pieces. They will be snug but, should snap together.
  2. File the hole on the handle so the pin slides freely through it. Assemble the handle by glueing the 2 grips together over the handle. Once this has dried connect the handle to the UFO top using the pins. you shouldn't need to glue the pins but, you can if you want to.
  3. Glue the Tracker-beam to the bottom of the UFO. It should fit around the circle quit nicely.
  4. Now you slide the Neo Pixel Ring up the Tracker-beam and mark the holes that your going to drill.
  5. Glue the bottom of the glass to the moon.
  6. If your going to use the battery clip you can screw it in. I used #4 1/2inch screw
  7. At this point your going to solder and assemble the electronics. The button and the battery wires go through the bottom of the moon through the tracker-beam and assemble in the UFO body.
    8.Once the electronics is working you can glue the top glass to the UFO and just snap the window in from the top to bottom. last slide the battery cover and snap it in no screws needed.
  8. Enjoy =)

comments.text:
I do a hot vapor polish
Use a asparagus pot (tall with a basket inside)
with a metal disc on the bottom of the basket to put the model on
2-3 tablespoons of acetone in the pot
model in basket on the disc. put all in the pot and heat for about 30 seconds
(I have a glass lid and you can see the acetone condense on the model
from the bottom up.)
once it is "wet" I take it off the heat, remove the basket from the pot.
in a minute I remove the model from the disc/basket
5-10 minutes later it is ready to go.
(sooner really but it smells for a bit till the acetone fully evaporates)

title: Mana Pillar - MTG: Arena of the Planeswalkers

description.text:
Hey guys I recently purchased AotP (MTG: Arena of the Planeswalkers) it brought back a lot of memories of when I used to play Heroscape. The front box has Chandra fighting Jace from some pillar, but it is not included terrain in the set! I wanted to make some paper craft versions with this but I wanted to get a visual of what I wanted. On the box it is pretty evident that there are different designs on some of the pillars, but it only ever shows two. The current uploaded AotP.Mana.Pillar.1 is the three pillars in the background. I am still playing with the one Chandra is actually standing on.

I also included a blank file so that if you have the editing software you can create what ever design you want.

I based the height off of the AotP cyrptoliths in the Innistrad Master set, as well as an average hex size for Heroscape/AotP. This resulted in a square pillar with B & W of 3.5cm, by height of 9cm.

Still working on custom rules for AotP, but some suggestions:
Scale(same as cryptoliths)
A figure adjacent to a Mana Pillar may move to the top space by counting 4 spaces of movement.

Mana Source
At the begging of a players turn who controls a planeswalker who is currently on a Mana Pillar, role a 20 sided die. If the result is a 16 or higher draw an additional card this turn, and deal one damage to that Mana Pillar.
